I'd like to dive
into that a little bit and share

00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:05.096
my side of the story.

00:09:06.240 --> 00:09:07.519
The first thing we need to think about

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:10.420
is that it's all about the priority.

00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:14.039
The priority for us
is we want to deliver a unique,

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:18.280
memorable, and also
a consistent brand experience.

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:21.640
We do that through color primarily.

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:24.479
Here's a couple examples.

00:09:24.480 --> 00:09:25.939
Number one, here's a slide

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:28.750
with four different sets of boxes,

00:09:29.160 --> 00:09:35.640
brown, yellow, purple,
orange, red, blue, yellow, red.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.159
If I were to ask you, and tell
you that these are actually four logos.

00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:43.879
Now, what industry
do you think that they come from?

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:47.399
I'm going to plot twist
and give away the answer here,

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:51.960
but we've got black-and-white
versions of the companies.

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:56.160
It's UPS, FedEx, Postal Service, and DHL.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.332
Now you see when
it's just black and white,

00:10:00.500 --> 00:10:03.599
they just group together,
and there's unity there between them.

00:10:03.600 --> 00:10:07.599
If you squint your eyes,
it just looks like some shapes.

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:10.279
Now, look when I add the color in there.

00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:14.559
Boom, immediately you can see
that the brown and yellow with UPS,

00:10:14.560 --> 00:10:19.919
it immediately distinguishes itself
from FedEx, which is right next to it.

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:23.919
The use of color
as a categorical differentiator

00:10:23.920 --> 00:10:28.046
in brand design is incredibly
powerful and important.

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:31.572
Color gives important
identity information.

00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:33.759
Another example of how we use color

00:10:33.760 --> 00:10:37.999
is that we use it for scannability
and creating visual hierarchy.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:43.159
On this screen, we've got
three rows of light gray text that says,

00:10:43.160 --> 00:10:45.479
"Read me, read me, read me, read me,"

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:48.480
but where did your eye go to?

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:51.359
Obviously, your eye
went to the left column

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:53.759
where the third one down says,
"Made you look,"

00:10:53.760 --> 00:10:57.000
in a small red bold font.

00:10:58.160 --> 00:10:59.039
Why is that?

00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:01.199
The "Read me" text was 45 point.

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:04.759
It's much bigger,
and the red text is only 16 point.

00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:06.479
It's way smaller but obviously,

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:11.459
our brain is fine-tuned to look

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:15.120
for danger or any type of warning.

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:18.157
We're drawn to the color red.

00:11:18.560 --> 00:11:23.399
We got to be aware of that in terms
of the scannability with colors.

00:11:23.400 --> 00:11:27.199
Another example is you can use color tones

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:32.760
within the same color to create
a sense of vibe or beauty.

00:11:33.240 --> 00:11:36.599
It's really the nuance
between the color that does that.

00:11:36.600 --> 00:11:40.884
In this example,
I've just taken some beautiful artwork

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:47.240
that is a throwback to like a 1900s
Parisian artistry.

00:11:47.560 --> 00:11:48.559
You can see it's beautiful.

00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:51.159
They use a similar color palette,

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:55.560
but they use tones
in between the different ones.

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:02.599
The next point is that we use
color for brand perception,

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:06.199
and it's really built into our psychology.

00:12:06.200 --> 00:12:10.319
On this slide, you can see
there are three logos on the left,

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:12.439
Starbucks, McDonald's, and Burger King.

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:17.679
Then opposing side, there's three logos,
IRS, Postal Service, and IBM.

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:21.959
The ones on the left are very vibrant
and colorful and full of life,

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:24.687
and honestly, they're appetizing.

00:12:24.720 --> 00:12:26.399
Now you look on the ones on the right,

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:32.839
they're formal, casual,
dare I say boring, but at least you know

00:12:32.840 --> 00:12:35.879
that if you are going to
one of those companies,

00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:41.434
there's going to be a sense of sturdiness
and solid and all that stuff.

00:12:42.240 --> 00:12:47.319
Color psychology plays a major role
in how consumers make decisions,

00:12:47.320 --> 00:12:50.039
and actually up to 90%
of the initial impression

00:12:50.040 --> 00:12:52.160
comes from color itself.

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:55.559
It's a big deal when we set colors,

00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:58.972
we don't want to mess
with those very often.

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:02.440
Just to boil that down here,

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:04.999
some of the pain points
is that as a designer,

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.967
I am taught what correct
ratios are supposed to be.

00:13:10.680 --> 00:13:14.399
Even in my natural personality,
my whole life,

00:13:14.400 --> 00:13:18.279
I've been a detailed person, and I know
what looks good and what doesn't,

00:13:18.280 --> 00:13:20.319
and we have an eye for it.

00:13:20.320 --> 00:13:22.359
When we're told that, "Hey, you know what,

00:13:22.360 --> 00:13:24.599
the design that you did, it's beautiful,

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:26.559
but it does not meet the standards,"

00:13:26.560 --> 00:13:29.319
sometimes our ego can get in the way.

00:13:29.320 --> 00:13:32.573
That's a bummer, but that's part of life.

00:13:32.600 --> 00:13:34.418
We have to avoid that.

00:13:34.520 --> 00:13:37.279
Number two, sometimes
it's not the designer,

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:39.639
it can actually be the company owner.

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:42.539
Maybe you have a CEO who is just dead set

00:13:42.540 --> 00:13:45.439
