Deneb: I think it's an important question.

00:14:58.560 --> 00:15:00.479
I was super glad that the market agreed

00:15:00.480 --> 00:15:03.119
to do this presentation
with me because I think

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:07.319
it's important that we understand
where the brand site is coming from.

00:15:07.320 --> 00:15:12.959
This is the final question
that they can have in their mind is,

00:15:12.960 --> 00:15:14.999
"I put all this effort into it.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:16.488
Let me use it."

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:18.439
If you go to the next slide,

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:20.739
let me tell you the priority

00:15:20.740 --> 00:15:23.219
for accessibility professions.

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:26.679
Our priority is is similar in many ways.

00:15:26.680 --> 00:15:32.039
In fact, we want to get the content out
to the people who are coming to the site.

00:15:32.040 --> 00:15:37.039
We want to create fully accessible
content for all users equally.

00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:40.239
That's really the goal from
an accessibility perspective,

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:42.439
which is really when you think about it,

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:46.920
it's the same as a goal
from the brand perspective.

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:49.400
We all want to do it.

00:15:49.720 --> 00:15:53.999
The way we do it has changed a little,

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:58.599
or at least there are some standards
that guide how we need to do this.

00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:01.399
If you'll go to the next page, Mark.

00:16:01.400 --> 00:16:02.919
I want to run through just

00:16:02.920 --> 00:16:09.120
really quickly the history of color
accessibility standards.

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:12.959
In 1991 was when the first websites
started coming out,

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:16.054
and at that point, they were just text.

00:16:16.560 --> 00:16:18.119
That's all you got.

00:16:18.120 --> 00:16:20.799
The user could maybe
change the color of the text,

00:16:20.800 --> 00:16:24.279
they could change the background,
maybe, but the creator

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:26.759
of the website couldn't
do anything about that.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:28.159
It was just the text.

00:16:28.160 --> 00:16:34.320
If you go to the next, in '96,
you see, CSS1 was introduced.

00:16:34.600 --> 00:16:40.400
With CSS, now all of a sudden,
the developers could style their text

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:42.479
and they could style their background,

00:16:42.480 --> 00:16:45.574
and they could do whatever they wanted.

00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:48.242
For several years, right, then,

00:16:48.940 --> 00:16:53.000
styling on the web was like the Wild West,

00:16:53.240 --> 00:16:56.239
the developers did whatever they wanted
because they thought it was cool,

00:16:56.240 --> 00:16:58.359
or the designers designed
however they wanted,

00:16:58.360 --> 00:16:59.319
because they thought it was cool.

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:03.239
They didn't have any standards
to guide how they did that.

00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:06.380
Next point says that in 1999,

00:17:08.220 --> 00:17:10.679
WCAG 1.0 came out,

00:17:10.680 --> 00:17:15.800
the Web Content Accessibility
Guidelines in the first version.

00:17:17.480 --> 00:17:22.359
This was a great step
but in terms of the actual standards,

00:17:22.360 --> 00:17:24.040
it was pretty weak.

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:28.199
It says the standard for color
at that point

00:17:28.200 --> 00:17:31.559
was that the foreground and background
color combinations should provide

00:17:31.560 --> 00:17:34.319
enough contrast when viewed
by someone having color

00:17:34.320 --> 00:17:37.959
deficits or when viewed
on a black-and-white screen.

00:17:37.960 --> 00:17:40.039
It's a little nebulous
what that even means.

00:17:40.040 --> 00:17:45.519
In fact, they had a quick test
appended to WCAG 1.0,

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:48.019
that said that the recommended way
to check on this

00:17:48.020 --> 00:17:50.719
to make sure that it met these guidelines

00:17:50.720 --> 00:17:55.380
was that the web developer
ought to print off

00:17:55.420 --> 00:17:58.719
a page of the website on
a black-and-white printer,

00:17:58.720 --> 00:18:00.786
and then go photocopy it.

00:18:00.920 --> 00:18:02.759
Then go photocopy
the thing that came from that,

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:04.359
and then do that a few times,

00:18:04.360 --> 00:18:07.759
and then hold it up and see
if they could still read it.

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:13.200
It's this crazy standard,
but it was at least a place to start.

00:18:13.480 --> 00:18:18.379
Next slide shows that the next version

00:18:18.380 --> 00:18:21.360
of WCAG 2.0 came out in 2008.

00:18:21.680 --> 00:18:23.199
That's where the familiar standard,

00:18:23.200 --> 00:18:29.280
which most people hopefully know about,
is that the contrast ratio

00:18:29.880 --> 00:18:32.219
between the foreground or the text

00:18:32.220 --> 00:18:34.659
and the background needs to be 4.5:1,

00:18:34.660 --> 00:18:38.519
meaning the text needs
to be four and a half times

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:44.040
brighter or darker than the background,
in order to be fully legible.

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:50.319
That was 2.0 in WCAG 2.0,
and also 2.1 adopted that same standard,

00:18:50.320 --> 00:18:55.175
also 2.2 adopted that standard,
though if you go to the next point,

00:18:55.176 --> 00:19:00.760
WCAG 3.0 is rumored,
at least in the draft,

00:19:01.360 --> 00:19:03.599
it looks like they're going to adopt

00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:08.280
the APCA values
instead of contrast ratios.

00:19:09.214 --> 00:19:11.880
APCA is a complex topic.

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:14.039
I don't fully understand it.

00:19:14.040 --> 00:19:16.139
If you do want to understand it,
you want to get into it,

00:19:16.140 --> 00:19:21.079
go to the Axon towards
the beginning of the year.

00:19:21.080 --> 00:19:23.759
They had a great session on this,
so you can check that out.

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:27.727
I also have a link to that
in our notes at the end.

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:29.879
If you go to the next slide,

00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:35.279
the real issue
is that with any of these standards

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:39.439
is that it's problematic
to use some brand colors,

00:19:39.440 --> 00:19:43.519
like if you've got
a flaming yellow or green,

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:46.599
really light color,
it's problematic to use that color

00:19:46.600 --> 00:19:50.160
in most situations for accessible content.

00:19:51.440 --> 00:19:54.619
For example, let's look at a brand color

00:19:54.620 --> 00:19:59.000
that's easily recognizable, Coca-Cola.

00:19:59.480 --> 00:20:03.919
Mark, would you tell us what you see
in this giant Coca-Cola label?

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:05.999
Mark: Right, so as a logo designer,

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:09.839
I would say there's a ton of personality,
there's a ton of contrast,

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:12.839
it pops off the screen against the white.

00:20:12.840 --> 00:20:15.359
I would say this is a historic logo,

00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:19.119
been around since late 1800s,
I think it looks great.

00:20:19.120 --> 00:20:23.166
What about for building
content around these colors?

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:24.999
Deneb: Great question.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.959
In this slide,
we still have the logo there,

00:20:27.960 --> 00:20:30.159
but now we're looking at the actual color,

00:20:30.160 --> 00:20:34.858
this Coca-Cola red,
very recognizable, f40000,

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:38.519
and the contrast ratio that that color

00:20:38.520 --> 00:20:43.020
has against the white
background is 4.33:1.

00:20:43.380 --> 00:20:47.679
Remember, the WCAG guidelines
say that the contrast ratio

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:50.820
for text needs to be 4.5:1.

00:20:50.860 --> 00:20:54.720
If you're going to use this on text,

00:20:55.160 --> 00:21:01.550
or use this as a color in your text,
it wouldn't work, it fails that.

00:21:03.720 --> 00:21:06.119
Let's look real quick
at just one other example.

00:21:06.120 --> 00:21:12.279
In this next page, we've got Burger King,
the old logo for Burger King.

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:15.559
Now tell me just
a little bit about this old

00:21:15.560 --> 00:21:17.319
logo that changed several years ago.

00:21:17.320 --> 00:21:22.279
Mark: Right, so again, as a logo designer,
you're wanting to make it pop,

00:21:22.280 --> 00:21:24.039
you're wanting to have lots of contrast,

00:21:24.040 --> 00:21:28.320
I see primary colors of blue,
yellow, and red.

00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:33.960
I think it does the job as a logo,
but obviously, it can be dated.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:38.759
In terms of building
content from these colors,

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:41.639
what do you have to say about that?

00:21:41.640 --> 00:21:46.799
Deneb: The problem with this old
logo was the yellow and even the red.

00:21:46.800 --> 00:21:49.799
The red is almost the same color
as the Coca-Cola red, which means

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:54.239
it's just a little shy of
the guidelines in terms

00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:57.360
of being able to use it in content.

00:21:57.646 --> 00:21:59.580
It's 4.3:1.

00:22:00.760 --> 00:22:02.299
The yellow is just 1.87:1,

00:22:02.300 --> 00:22:05.519
so you definitely
couldn't use that in content.

00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:08.040
The blue-on-white does work

00:22:08.080 --> 00:22:10.199
but then Burger King did
something interesting.

00:22:10.200 --> 00:22:13.319
If you go to the next slide,
this shows their new logo.

00:22:13.320 --> 00:22:17.839
Notice the orange color is a little darker

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:20.079
than their yellow
was from the previous one,

00:22:20.080 --> 00:22:22.559
and the red color is darker as well.

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:25.919
The whole thing is set
on this tan background,

00:22:25.920 --> 00:22:29.279
which actually means
that the red on tan and the orange on tan,

00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:33.880
neither of those could actually
be used in content either.

00:22:34.920 --> 00:22:39.039
The next slide shows
that though these are still problematic,

00:22:39.040 --> 00:22:42.848
this color migration did
something cool for them.

00:22:43.120 --> 00:22:46.819
It paved the way for them
to include a new accessible color

00:22:46.820 --> 00:22:49.679
that if you go to
the next slide, this brown,

00:22:49.680 --> 00:22:53.399
this is a snapshot
of their site right now.

00:22:53.400 --> 00:22:57.526
See how they use that brown
color in a lot of places.

00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:04.760
By migrating the colors of their brand,

00:23:05.520 --> 00:23:10.439
they were able to introduce this color
that's very, very useful to them.

00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:15.121
In fact, interestingly,
notice this button is their new red.

00:23:15.280 --> 00:23:17.179
I told you that against tan
it doesn't work,

00:23:17.180 --> 00:23:22.739
but the button text is actually white

00:23:22.740 --> 00:23:26.072
and against white,
that red color can work.

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:29.519
They're fudging it a little bit,

00:23:29.520 --> 00:23:32.039
but they're using it in an accessible way,

00:23:32.040 --> 00:23:34.940
which I think is really pretty cool.

00:23:36.040 --> 00:23:38.279
Then the next slide just shows
kind of more details about that.

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:43.360
The brown has a tremendous contrast ratio.

00:23:43.440 --> 00:23:46.919
Go ahead on the next slide
if you want to, Mark.

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:47.859
Mark: All right.

00:23:47.860 --> 00:23:52.079
We saw how logos can work
great in terms of color,

00:23:52.080 --> 00:23:56.879
but when you're building the content,
it's a different animal.

00:23:56.880 --> 00:24:02.159
What do the rules actually say
about text from a logo or brand name?

00:24:02.160 --> 00:24:03.119
Deneb: That is a good question.

00:24:03.120 --> 00:24:06.179
On the next slide, we have WCAG 2.0

00:24:06.180 --> 00:24:09.799
success criterion 1.4.3
says text that is part

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:13.846
of a logo or brand name
has no contrast requirement.

00:24:16.560 --> 00:24:19.919
Mark: Brand colors don't need
to be accessible, right?

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:20.879
Deneb: Not quite.

00:24:20.880 --> 00:24:22.399
There is a caveat.

00:24:22.400 --> 00:24:29.160
The content does need to follow
those accessibility guidelines.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.039
That's the heart of the issue here

00:24:32.040 --> 00:24:36.759
is we're looking at the fact that we need

00:24:36.760 --> 00:24:43.240
to distinguish between brand
colors and content colors, essentially.

00:24:44.560 --> 00:24:47.122
If you'll go to the next slide,

00:24:48.800 --> 00:24:50.399
we'll see that we're talking about

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:52.479
the Web Content
Accessibility Guideline here.

00:24:52.480 --> 00:24:55.399
The content is the important thing.

00:24:55.400 --> 00:25:02.119
To go to what that is, we've got
basically what content is any information

00:25:02.120 --> 00:25:05.056
that's communicated through the site.

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:11.720
Let's look at the separation of content

00:25:13.720 --> 00:25:15.459
and branding real quick.

00:25:15.460 --> 00:25:17.196
Go ahead to the next.

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:18.779
Mark: Right.

00:25:18.780 --> 00:25:22.099
What we did is we're separating
now the idea

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:25.000
of brand color versus content color.

00:25:26.080 --> 00:25:29.679
Let's take a look back
at our friend Coca-Cola.

00:25:29.680 --> 00:25:33.239
The branding of it is the packaging,

00:25:33.240 --> 00:25:36.479
the logos, the can design, all that stuff.

00:25:36.480 --> 00:25:40.999
The content/UI, obviously,
is the content on the website,

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:45.599
the buttons, the titles,
the container boxes, et cetera.

00:25:45.740 --> 00:25:48.599
If you look at their website,
it looks great.

00:25:48.600 --> 00:25:52.559
It's still a branded experience
because they're using

00:25:52.560 --> 00:25:55.439
the pictures of the cans as artwork,

00:25:55.440 --> 00:25:59.566
and yet they've separated
the content in its own box.

00:25:59.751 --> 00:26:02.759
Not dialogue box, but its own container.

00:26:02.760 --> 00:26:05.520
Again, separating the two.

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:11.239
Deneb: Looking back
at this previous slide that we did,

00:26:11.240 --> 00:26:13.119
what is an example of content?

00:26:13.120 --> 00:26:16.611
I've got four that you guys
need to focus on.

00:26:16.840 --> 00:26:17.779
Paragraphs.

00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:23.175
paragraph text needs to meet
that content color requirement of 4.5:1.

00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:26.839
The headings need to meet that.

00:26:26.840 --> 00:26:28.079
Links and buttons.

00:26:28.080 --> 00:26:31.919
Now, over the next several slides,
let's look very quickly over some sites

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:35.159
that maybe don't follow
those best practices.

00:26:35.160 --> 00:26:38.839
The first slide here,
we've got showing some headings

00:26:38.840 --> 00:26:42.886
that is in their brand
orange that they really love.

00:26:43.200 --> 00:26:46.679
Unfortunately, the orange
has a contrast ratio of just 2:1,

00:26:46.680 --> 00:26:50.059
which many people
with good eyesight are not going

00:26:50.060 --> 00:26:53.159
to have trouble reading
but if there are some challenges,

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:58.019
some contrast sensitivity challenges
there, can you go on to the next?

00:26:58.020 --> 00:26:59.408
How about now?

00:27:00.120 --> 00:27:03.452
Can you still read
what those headings say?

00:27:05.240 --> 00:27:07.479
All I did, I took the same
image and I just decreased

00:27:07.480 --> 00:27:11.595
the contrast of that image by 67%

00:27:11.880 --> 00:27:17.839
which is actually
the same reduction, generally,

00:27:17.840 --> 00:27:23.080
of contrast sensitivity that people
see between ages 20 and 60.

00:27:23.160 --> 00:27:25.839
We'll talk a little bit about
that later on.

00:27:25.840 --> 00:27:30.399
Just notice how difficult it is to read
those headings.

00:27:30.400 --> 00:27:35.478
In the next slide, we see
the same kind of issue, but with links.

00:27:35.480 --> 00:27:40.479
We've got some links
that have a lower contrast ratio

00:27:40.480 --> 00:27:44.119
and then some text even below them
that have an even lower one.

00:27:44.120 --> 00:27:46.021
These need to be fixed.

00:27:48.720 --> 00:27:49.959
They're just problematic.

00:27:49.960 --> 00:27:54.279
Then our last example here
is going to be with a button.

00:27:54.280 --> 00:27:57.319
This button is a yellow button
with white text.

00:27:57.320 --> 00:28:00.467
I suspect that the reason they had
that yellow button and white text

00:28:00.468 --> 00:28:03.219
was because they thought
the button would pop out

00:28:03.220 --> 00:28:06.120
and the text makes it pop even more.

00:28:07.240 --> 00:28:11.719
My question is,
does that white-on-yellow really pop?

00:28:11.720 --> 00:28:15.119
If you'll go to next slide,
it says, how about now?

00:28:15.120 --> 00:28:18.359
Once again, I decreased
the contrast and you see

00:28:18.360 --> 00:28:22.119
it's very difficult to read
what that button says

00:28:22.120 --> 00:28:25.373
now with that contrast a little bit less.

00:28:26.120 --> 00:28:29.199
I know that we're preaching
to the choir, right?

00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:32.879
You guys are all here because you love
accessibility and you want

00:28:32.880 --> 00:28:38.275
to make sure that your WordPress
sites are as accessible as possible.

00:28:38.320 --> 00:28:40.839
You're faced
with this secondary question here.

00:28:40.840 --> 00:28:44.479
How do I persuade my boss
or my brand manager?

00:28:44.480 --> 00:28:48.240
I have Mark talk a little bit about this.

00:28:48.400 --> 00:28:50.759
What takeaways do you have, Mark?

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:51.619
Mark: Great.

00:28:51.620 --> 00:28:54.519
We got three takeaways again for you guys.

00:28:54.520 --> 00:28:58.319
The first of those three really comes
down to the data.

00:28:58.320 --> 00:29:00.000
data tells a story.

00:29:00.760 --> 00:29:03.719
Now, if we take a look at this example,

00:29:03.720 --> 00:29:06.656
this is an example of colorblindness.

00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:08.999
the photos on the right, on the top right,

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:12.359
you have just a regular photo
of green and red apples.

00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:15.239
Now on the bottom right,
you've got the same picture,

00:29:15.240 --> 00:29:18.000
but simulated as colorblindness.

00:29:18.120 --> 00:29:23.159
You can see that you can no longer
easily distinguish between the two.

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:24.859
There's a lot of stats on this.

00:29:24.860 --> 00:29:27.680
Deneb, what are the stats on this?

00:29:28.320 --> 00:29:30.019
Deneb: The reason
why you might want to show

00:29:30.020 --> 00:29:33.479
an image like this and present
the statistics to your boss

00:29:33.480 --> 00:29:35.599
is because I think
it drives the point home.

00:29:35.600 --> 00:29:40.043
The statistic is that 4.25%
of all people are colorblind.

00:29:40.200 --> 00:29:47.120
That's basically 1 in 12 biological
men and 1 in 200 biological women.

00:29:47.400 --> 00:29:49.320
Ends up being 4.25%.

00:29:49.480 --> 00:29:54.079
That's over all people that are out
there and all people online.

00:29:54.080 --> 00:29:56.160
That's a lot of people.

00:29:56.280 --> 00:30:02.072
so present this stat and I think
you can get some traction with your boss.

00:30:02.680 --> 00:30:08.640
Mark: The next one here is poor eyesight
or myopia or nearsightedness.

00:30:08.840 --> 00:30:12.559
You can see on the right-hand side,
top right, you've got a normal image.

00:30:12.560 --> 00:30:17.120
On the bottom right,
someone who has myopia.

00:30:18.600 --> 00:30:23.043
Tell me a little bit more about
the stats on this, Deneb.

00:30:23.720 --> 00:30:26.099
Deneb: Across demographics that I found,

00:30:26.100 --> 00:30:32.039
30% of people have myopia
in the world or I think it's in the world.

00:30:32.040 --> 00:30:33.359
It might be in just America,

00:30:33.360 --> 00:30:38.834
but that's still a lot of people
wearing glasses, for nearsightedness.

00:30:39.520 --> 00:30:44.319
there was a study done that showed
that there's an inverse relationship

00:30:44.320 --> 00:30:50.079
between contrast sensitivity and myopia,
meaning the more myopic you are,

00:30:50.080 --> 00:30:53.174
the less contrast sensitivity you have.

00:30:54.800 --> 00:31:00.433
That means that sensitivity has gone
down in that entire 30% population.

00:31:01.780 --> 00:31:02.979
Mark: That's a lot.

00:31:02.980 --> 00:31:06.840
The next example
is just plain out poor eyesight.

00:31:07.080 --> 00:31:10.199
As we age, our retina gets a little older,

00:31:10.200 --> 00:31:12.439
or if we're sick or something like that.

00:31:12.440 --> 00:31:13.919
Just to illustrate that purpose,

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:17.159
the picture on the right
is your standard old

00:31:17.160 --> 00:31:20.719
Honda that you drove
in high school or something like that.

00:31:20.720 --> 00:31:25.999
Over the years, the headlamp gets
the UV damage to it and it yellows

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:29.263
and it gets a lot harder
to see through that.

00:31:29.264 --> 00:31:32.320
Deneb, what are some stats on aging?

00:31:33.240 --> 00:31:37.679
Deneb: The same thing happens
to your cornea, it turns out.

00:31:37.680 --> 00:31:39.839
Actually, it yellows as well.

00:31:39.840 --> 00:31:42.599
As it yellows, less light comes in.

00:31:42.600 --> 00:31:46.679
The stat is that the amount
of light reaching

00:31:46.680 --> 00:31:52.000
your retina declines 67%
between ages 20 and 60.

00:31:52.320 --> 00:31:54.479
That's a significant amount

00:31:54.480 --> 00:31:57.359
of light that isn't making
it to your retina,

00:31:57.360 --> 00:32:00.679
that influences the contrast sensitivity.

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:02.581
It's a whole lot lower.

00:32:03.820 --> 00:32:04.659
That's it.

00:32:04.660 --> 00:32:09.400
16% of the population
are above 60, I guess.

00:32:10.680 --> 00:32:14.719
I've got a pie chart on this slide
showing 16% aging retina,

00:32:14.720 --> 00:32:18.979
30% myopia, 4.25% colorblindness.

00:32:18.980 --> 00:32:24.040
That leads to only 49.75%
having standard eyesight.

00:32:24.120 --> 00:32:26.351
If we go to the next slide,

00:32:26.546 --> 00:32:33.546
this shows that over 50.25% of visitors

00:32:33.780 --> 00:32:40.080
to any site have some sort
of visual impairment.

00:32:40.640 --> 00:32:45.999
The question that you can ask
your boss or your brand manager,

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:50.960
do we really want to serve
the 4.25% the 33% the 16%?

00:32:52.080 --> 00:32:55.799
Do we want the business and goodwill
of this half of our visitors?

00:32:55.800 --> 00:32:59.760
I think probably the answer
will be, yes, we do.

00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:02.919
Mark: That's great. Great point.

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:06.919
Number two, we can talk
about a little peer pressure.

00:33:06.920 --> 00:33:09.839
All right. Everyone's doing it.

00:33:09.840 --> 00:33:11.880
You know you want to.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:14.639
In my time at some of these companies,

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:16.799
I've had a chance to look
at the brand guides

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:19.693
and the human interface guidelines.

00:33:19.840 --> 00:33:20.879
They've done a great job.

00:33:20.880 --> 00:33:24.699
A lot of these major brands
have migrated to more accessible colors

00:33:24.700 --> 00:33:26.959
over the years and they've stuck with it.

00:33:26.960 --> 00:33:30.600
Microsoft, Apple, Coca-Cola, Burger King.

00:33:30.720 --> 00:33:33.679
Just looking at Apple's website
from a little while ago,

00:33:33.680 --> 00:33:36.079
you can see they still
have beautiful imagery

00:33:36.080 --> 00:33:40.599
that they use, but they separate
out the content and the headline

00:33:40.600 --> 00:33:43.559
and the subheading and the buttons.

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:45.874
They are separate from that.

00:33:46.480 --> 00:33:51.419
Then looking at Microsoft,
what they do is they have a content box

00:33:51.420 --> 00:33:53.639
on top of the beautiful imagery.

00:33:53.640 --> 00:33:55.919
Again, separating out those two things,

00:33:55.920 --> 00:33:59.039
making sure there's clear enough contrast.

00:33:59.040 --> 00:34:01.199
Then on the other side of the spectrum,

00:34:01.200 --> 00:34:04.532
Baskin-Robbins, they use the bright color.

00:34:04.800 --> 00:34:07.399
It's not just black and white type.

00:34:07.400 --> 00:34:09.639
They've got lots of personality here,

00:34:09.640 --> 00:34:12.599
but they use a dark brown content box.

00:34:12.600 --> 00:34:17.559
Then even in their hero image,
they have a lot of the bright contrast

00:34:17.560 --> 00:34:19.119
between the pink and the white.

00:34:19.120 --> 00:34:21.199
Then they've set up
their color scheme to work

00:34:21.200 --> 00:34:25.326
so that all three triangulate
and they work together.

00:34:27.120 --> 00:34:30.135
The third one we'd like to talk about,

00:34:30.480 --> 00:34:32.839
it's called the magic of tint and shades.

00:34:32.840 --> 00:34:38.076
As a brand designer, one thing
that we create is a color step ramp.

00:34:38.280 --> 00:34:41.279
Basically, the main point is,

00:34:41.280 --> 00:34:43.439
what I want to bring
to your guys' attention,

00:34:43.440 --> 00:34:45.679
everything digital that we're creating,

00:34:45.680 --> 00:34:50.282
it's just our best guess
at recreating the world around us.

00:34:51.720 --> 00:34:56.399
When you think about the world,
you look down at the ground,

00:34:56.400 --> 00:34:59.239
there's a whole bunch
of shadows and lights

00:34:59.240 --> 00:35:01.199
and highlights and all that stuff.

00:35:01.200 --> 00:35:04.799
It's not just one color and yet in brand,

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:09.519
we try to get everything just
in this jail of these certain colors.

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:13.566
I really think there's more wiggle
room around that.

00:35:13.680 --> 00:35:16.159
Who of you guys remember this?

00:35:17.057 --> 00:35:20.879
In 2020, it was that whole
controversy that went viral about,

00:35:20.880 --> 00:35:25.085
is this dress white and gold,
or is it blue and black?

00:35:25.400 --> 00:35:28.919
It was this crazy phenomenon
where it really depended

00:35:28.920 --> 00:35:32.359
on how you were viewing
the photo on the screen.

00:35:32.360 --> 00:35:35.692
Were you seeing
it with or black around it?

00:35:35.920 --> 00:35:38.279
Our eyes have different
sensitivities based

00:35:38.280 --> 00:35:41.599
on the amount of cones
that we have in them.

00:35:41.600 --> 00:35:43.479
Just to break that down,

00:35:43.480 --> 00:35:47.447
let's say someone
has a more yellow-leaning vision,

00:35:47.480 --> 00:35:50.240
they're seeing it that way.

00:35:50.400 --> 00:35:53.199
Then on the other side of it,
they're seeing a different way,

00:35:53.200 --> 00:35:56.480
but really it's the exact same color.

00:35:57.280 --> 00:36:02.319
Our perception of color
is really at the mercy

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:04.634
of some different variables.

00:36:05.280 --> 00:36:08.612
First and foremost,
the lighting around it.

00:36:10.080 --> 00:36:13.279
The accuracy of our perception
of a color depends

00:36:13.280 --> 00:36:16.560
on the conditions that play around it.

00:36:17.040 --> 00:36:19.679
For example, highlights and shadows.

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:23.759
For this example, I've got
a single piece of paper on the left.

00:36:23.760 --> 00:36:25.579
You can see that it's in the sunlight

00:36:25.580 --> 00:36:28.559
and there's shadows that are cast over it.

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:29.999
It's not really a trick.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:32.799
This is really what we're looking at.

00:36:32.800 --> 00:36:35.759
If we were to really dissect this down,

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:38.919
that single piece of paper
is creating two colors.

00:36:38.920 --> 00:36:43.239
You've got the light gray,
which technically is white,

00:36:43.240 --> 00:36:48.199
and then you've got the dark gray,
which is the white plus shadow.

00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:49.919
You see that in nature as well.

00:36:49.920 --> 00:36:52.699
With this image, you've got leaves

00:36:52.700 --> 00:36:55.639
that have shadow
and sunlight on top of them.

00:36:55.640 --> 00:36:59.439
Again, the color of the leaf
in the sunlight is light green

00:36:59.440 --> 00:37:01.359
and the color of the leaf in
the shadows is dark green,

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:03.261
but it's the same leaf.

00:37:04.160 --> 00:37:09.640
We can apply that exact same
principle to the use of brand colors.

00:37:10.080 --> 00:37:13.679
We do this through what we call
tint and shade ramps.

00:37:13.680 --> 00:37:16.080
Now, as a brand designer,

00:37:16.440 --> 00:37:22.079
the goal of this is to build
a versatile tonal system of tints

00:37:22.080 --> 00:37:26.360
and shades that we can basically call
approved colors.

00:37:26.760 --> 00:37:30.439
It's a workaround that if we need
some more accessible

00:37:30.440 --> 00:37:33.479
colors and they're not in the brand guide,

00:37:33.480 --> 00:37:36.379
we can maybe present
this option to them and say,

00:37:36.380 --> 00:37:39.950
"Hey, let's look
at it from this perspective."

00:37:40.040 --> 00:37:44.799
Again, back to our example,
sunlight is basically like the brand color

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:49.639
plus 20% white or whatever,
and then the shadow on the leaf is brand

00:37:49.640 --> 00:37:52.439
color plus 20% black or whatever.

00:37:52.440 --> 00:37:56.804
As an example,
this is what a tint ramp could look like.

00:37:56.920 --> 00:38:00.559
You've got your primary color,
it's just a bucket of paint basically,

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:02.791
and then you add 20% white,

00:38:03.040 --> 00:38:06.159
it brings it up another 20%
now you're at 40%

00:38:06.160 --> 00:38:08.970
and it goes all the way up to 100.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:14.159
This is a six-step tint ramp,
and then this is a six-step shade ramp.

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:16.839
Again, you've got the brand color,

00:38:16.840 --> 00:38:20.839
you add 20% steps
until it gets to the darker colors.

00:38:20.840 --> 00:38:22.679
You're still within the brand color,

00:38:22.680 --> 00:38:26.199
and yet we're using
the principle of shading

00:38:26.200 --> 00:38:29.319
or lighting in order
to alter that a little bit.

00:38:29.320 --> 00:38:32.319
This is a real-life example of a tint ramp

00:38:32.320 --> 00:38:34.439
that we made for a SeaMonster customer,

00:38:34.440 --> 00:38:36.119
and they had a really vibrant color

00:38:36.120 --> 00:38:39.399
scheme with all of these different colors.

00:38:39.400 --> 00:38:43.759
I made this ramp and we were able to use
all of these colors

00:38:43.760 --> 00:38:48.480
in approved areas
and it helped us tremendously.

00:38:49.720 --> 00:38:54.439
Now we're at the point where hopefully
we've talked you into it,

00:38:54.440 --> 00:38:58.239
but the question is,
where can we use the original brand colors

00:38:58.240 --> 00:39:02.199
if now we have to just make things
black and white or whatever?

00:39:02.200 --> 00:39:04.959
The short answer is,
it's basically anywhere

00:39:04.960 --> 00:39:07.191
that's not content-bearing.

00:39:07.640 --> 00:39:11.839
Artwork, photography,
color bars, all that stuff.

00:39:11.840 --> 00:39:14.639
The longer, more complicated
answer is it's up

00:39:14.640 --> 00:39:17.972
to you and your brand
team to work through,

00:39:18.840 --> 00:39:20.999
and there's a lot of nuance there.

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:24.279
Again, it's about not seeing
each other as enemies.

00:39:24.280 --> 00:39:26.759
You guys are on the same team.

00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:31.799
We put a list of stuff together
just to get the creative juices going,

00:39:31.800 --> 00:39:33.719
and you probably have your own list,

00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:38.519
but you can get color pops
in the photography or illustrations

00:39:38.520 --> 00:39:42.646
or in whatever artwork
and then separate the content.

00:39:43.920 --> 00:39:45.399
How about section dividers?

00:39:45.400 --> 00:39:47.639
Let's say you have your landing section

00:39:47.640 --> 00:39:50.159
and then you're going
into another section below it.

00:39:50.160 --> 00:39:54.679
Just give a nice big color
bar there and some tagline

00:39:54.680 --> 00:39:59.840
or whatever in a bright white
color or something.

00:40:00.240 --> 00:40:01.299
Patterns.

00:40:01.300 --> 00:40:03.839
You see patterns used behind things,

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:06.599
but you can use them as art treatments.

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:09.119
Any other graphic treatments like creating

00:40:09.120 --> 00:40:12.849
your photography
to be bitmap or duotone images.

00:40:13.160 --> 00:40:16.119
Again, all of this stuff
is probably predetermined

00:40:16.120 --> 00:40:19.919
by your brand manager
if you are a bigger brand,

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:23.479
but if you're just mom-and-pop
boutique thing,

00:40:23.480 --> 00:40:27.119
it's up to us to come
up with these solutions.

00:40:27.120 --> 00:40:32.832
On the accessibility professional side,
you've got a couple to share too.

