Marina: All right.

00:47:36.360 --> 00:47:40.559
Is applying a CSS text-shadow
behind a white text

00:47:40.560 --> 00:47:44.360
an effective way to fix
a poor contrast ratio?

00:47:46.840 --> 00:47:50.559
Mark: We're going to have probably
slightly different answers to this one.

00:47:50.560 --> 00:47:55.680
This definitely goes back
to our core values and training.

00:47:56.480 --> 00:47:58.999
I'll just say five seconds
on this and then Deneb,

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.400
and feel free to jump in.

00:48:01.600 --> 00:48:04.039
This is one of the first things
they tell you in design

00:48:04.040 --> 00:48:07.359
school that you have to be really careful.

00:48:07.360 --> 00:48:09.759
You want text to speak for itself.

00:48:09.760 --> 00:48:13.119
You don't want to put strokes around it.

00:48:13.120 --> 00:48:18.400
You don't want to apply shadows
to it that are not necessary.

00:48:18.640 --> 00:48:21.239
If you have to do that,
then you have not created

00:48:21.240 --> 00:48:25.880
a background good enough
that allows for enough contrast.

00:48:27.920 --> 00:48:31.959
My understanding
is that from the designer standpoint,

00:48:31.960 --> 00:48:36.979
that's not something that we would
be encouraging because it messes

00:48:36.980 --> 00:48:43.639
with more than just the contrast ratio.

00:48:43.640 --> 00:48:46.919
It messes with the aesthetic
and the beauty of it.

00:48:46.920 --> 00:48:50.966
That has its own special
purpose to create a shadow.

00:48:52.200 --> 00:48:53.880
That's my opinion.

00:48:54.480 --> 00:48:58.079
Again, we might have slightly
different opinions and that's okay.

00:48:58.080 --> 00:49:02.920
Deneb: We have actually butted
heads over this a couple times.

00:49:03.120 --> 00:49:06.679
It may not be good from
a design perspective.

00:49:06.680 --> 00:49:08.399
It's not good, as Mark has told us.

00:49:08.400 --> 00:49:12.680
However, from an accessibility
rules perspective,

00:49:13.200 --> 00:49:19.359
it does make it pass the rule.

00:49:19.360 --> 00:49:23.039
I mean, yes, it can be used,
but it's not a good idea.

00:49:23.040 --> 00:49:27.339
Better is to never have text over an image

00:49:27.340 --> 00:49:30.559
that's too light or
too dark to be legible.

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:34.799
Now, the way that you can check
that one out in this appendix page

00:49:34.800 --> 00:49:39.243
as well is the link on the video
to the Firefox DevTools.

00:49:39.920 --> 00:49:43.559
Firefox is the only place
I've found that actually,

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:48.240
it has a way to determine
the range of contrast

00:49:48.960 --> 00:49:54.200
ratios of text
over an image or a gradient background.

00:49:54.600 --> 00:49:56.679
That'll show you if you need

00:49:56.680 --> 00:50:01.559
to make the background image
substantially lighter

00:50:01.560 --> 00:50:04.919
so that a dark overlaying text works

00:50:04.920 --> 00:50:07.919
or substantially
darker if a lighter over--

00:50:07.920 --> 00:50:11.839
That's how you can figure out
if you've actually accomplished that.

00:50:11.840 --> 00:50:16.439
Better than that, though,
is just not to have text over an image.

00:50:16.440 --> 00:50:20.279
I think Mark and I have both come
to the agreement.

00:50:20.280 --> 00:50:24.279
He'd rather separate
and not have the text over the image.

00:50:24.280 --> 00:50:28.559
He said that's a good design
choice and he had to put it on top.

00:50:28.560 --> 00:50:30.560
It's better to separate.

